<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. Description of the Country around Lakes Superior and Huron, 1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0018</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">purple colour and <span class="DelHand-author">assume</span> <span class="AddHand-author">acquire</span> that agreeable yet medicinal acid that I believe has no equal.  It is a fact of which I have had Repeated experience that the abundant use of fresh Cranberrys will cure pleurisy in its worst Stages and works a tauer miracle in liquifying the blood than ever the worthy of S<sup>t</sup> Januarius did<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Wild flowers in this country are few in number and neither attract by their colours or Odour<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Of Mosses there is a Vast and beautiful Variety but as I am unaquainted with their qualities and with the botanical mode of describing them <span class="AddHand-author">I Shall leave them</span> as well as the insects, to the first Butterfly hunter who may favour this part of the world with a visit, and mankind with the Result of his useful Researches<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The quadrupeds and birds of this country have been so well and accurately described by Buffon that little more could be said on the Subject and nothing added to the list<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I shall only Observe that the Indians utterly deny that the Beaver ever tastes fish<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  I must here mention a curious circumstance related to me a few days ago by a young hunter whom I had Sent into the country last Autumn North East</p>

